node.text:
Beyond honored to present the @SaintHeron’s first podcast with the incomparable visual artist and novelist, Barbara Chase-Riboud and author and educator Ilyasah Shabazz. (Link in Bio)

Shabazz recounts her childhood as one of Betty Shabazz and Malcolm X’s six daughters, the intentional and spiritual substance of her children's and YA literary works, and her community building work with The Malcolm X & Dr. Betty Shabazz Memorial and Educational Center.
Chase-Riboud retells memories of being the first Black woman to integrate the school of architecture at Yale University, the literary construction of her visionary museum of history’s invisible women, and a direct confrontation when her original novel Echo of Lions was plagiarized and repackaged as Steven Spielberg’s ‘Amistad.’

Throughout the podcast, Chase-Riboud’s and Shabazz’s interests in history and genealogy are connected by juxtaposing Ilyasah's literature on Malcolm X and Barbara's 'Malcolm X' metal and fiber sculpture series. Together, they reflect on their earliest memories of an awareness of identity and weave the emotional significance of Black femininity into stories that demonstrate how they remained all but corrupted by the conditions of each circumstance.

Listen now on WWW.SAINTHERON.COM

node.text:
@SAINTHERON is a process. It is a moving, living and breathing evolution. It is a spirit. 
Like most of my projects, it started with a question.
A need. A call. A cry turned celebration. 

Nine years ago, I remember calling my team during the rollout of my True EP. I recognized what I was seeking most was to find community. To find a space that aspired to enrich and expand the world with the nuances, thoughts, and discovery through both individual and communal identities. 
It was in that moment, Saint Heron was birthed. 

Today Saint Heron transitions into an institution, studio, and agency with a mission to reimagine the urgency in building and preserving permanent collections and archives of our own artists’ works.
We wish to build a space that engages and protects radical conceptual imaginings across all facets of art, music, culture, and design. We are dedicated to becoming the historians of our own expressions.

I couldn’t move into this next chapter without thanking the two women who helped me birth Saint Heron from its roots, my dearest Armina Mussa and NyAsia Burris.

And to all who have come along the journey, there are no words to thank you for your support, and all of the ways you have personally helped us to grow. For making this a space where we don’t have to fill in the blanks, for understanding what is not always spoken. All of our projects are bricks Saint Heron Heron adds to history's foundation for tomorrow's imagined heights. 

Our community is a living testament to the glory of expression, and how that recharges and reaffirms what we hold for our own cultural and artistic worth.

Visit www.saintheron.com to learn more about the future of SAINT HERON
